///
/// "Setting program"
@Node "setting" "Setting One Assign"
@{b}Setting One Assign@{ub}

    So, all you need is assembly compiler. I think you can use anyone, but
I cannot guarantee that. The program was written using TrashmOne 1.6, so
this one will work.

    As there are four main types of assign command, the program (and data
as well) are divided to three parts.
    The first part is for normal assigns. It is the same as you write e.g.
@{b}ASSIGN@{ub} @{i}abc:@{ui} @{i}SYS:Libs@{ui}.
    The second one is for multiple assigns. The ASSIGN command example is
e.g. @{b}ASSIGN@{ub} @{i}abc:@{ui} @{i}SYS:C@{ui} @{b}ADD@{ub}. It means, that if any program will look for
file @{i}abc:xyz@{ui}, AmigaDOS will first search in @{i}SYS:Libs@{ui} directory as we
assigned it first and if this file is not there, it will search through
@{i}SYS:C@{ui} directory. This is used e.g. in WB 3.0 for LIBS: assign (to SYS:Libs 
and SYS:Classes) and I'm using this one for fonts too (one directory for
BitMap fonts and the second one for Compugraphics outline ones).
    The third part is for late assigns. The ASSIGN command example is e.g.
@{b}ASSIGN@{ub} @{i}ijk:@{ui} @{i}SYS:@{ui} @{b}DEFER@{ub}. It means, that the assign won't be present to Amiga
until first use. It will not pop up in file requesters until anything will
ask AmigaDOS for @{i}ijk:@{ui} device. Then it will be assigned.
    The fourth, last one is for path assigns. The example:
@{b}ASSIGN@{ub} @{i}Floppy:@{ui} @{i}DF0:@{ui} @{b}PATH@{ub}. It means, that when anything will ask for Floppy:
it will go to currenly present disk in df0:, not to the one it was in drive
when assign was called.
    So if you don't want to use any part of these four ones, just put @{b};@{ub}
to the beginning of equivalent @{b}SET@{ub} command line at the beginning of the
program. NORMALASSIGNS stands for the first part, ADDASSIGNS for the second,
DEFERASSIGNS for the third and PATHASSINGS for the last one.

    And now how to tell program which assigns to make. As I wanted to make
the program the smallest it can be, it can't read command line arguments.
Instead of that you have to type everything into program and then compile
it. All three lists for all the three parts of program has the same syntax,
so it is:
                dc.b    '@{b}Path@{ub}',0,@{b}Name@{ub}',0
    The Path stands for the directory assign will be made to and Name
stands for the device assign will be made for. It's the same as the ASSIGN
command would look like ASSIGN Name: Path.
    The @{b}IMPORTANT THING@{ub} is that the Name in the list is @{u}without@{uu} the
'@{b}:@{ub}' character.
    One example: Assign for 'ENV:' to 'RAM:ENV' will look:
                dc.b    'RAM:ENV',0,'ENV',0
    Whole list is ended by
                dc.b    0
    There are all three lists I use so I hope you'll understand it. If not,
I'm sorry, you're missing quite good utility.
@EndNode
///
/// "Using program"
@Node "use" "Using One Assign"
    The program cannot be run from Workbench.
    The best thing is to run AllAssign in Startup-Sequence at the possition
you normaly run your first assign. And don't forget to delete all used
assigns in startup-sequence and in user-startup.
    Keep the source code so you can update the program whenever anything is
asking for it's own ASSIGN
@EndNode
///
/// "Requirements"
@Node "Reqs" Requirements
    One Assign requires AmigaDOS V37 at least for running
    One Assign requires assembly compiler and include files for compiling.

    One Assign wes developed using A1200 (Kickstart 39.106, Workbench 39.29)
with 203 MB Conner Hard disk (CP 30204).
    One Assign was tested under Kick and WB mentioned above and also under
Kickstart 37.175 and Workbench xx.xxx (again on A1200).
@EndNode
